 of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]},{"name":"Nicolao","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Dean\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which has a double origin. In part it is a local name for someone who lived in a valley (Middle English <i>dene</i>, Old English <i>denu</i>) and in part an occupational name for someone who served as a dean, i.e. ecclesiastical supervisor (Latin <i>decanus</i>). The given name also sometimes represents Italian <i>Dino</i> (a short form of names such as <i>Bernardino</i>), as in the case of the American actor and singer  Dean Martin  (  1917–95 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Dene","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Dean ."]},{"name":"Deane","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which has a double origin. In part it is a local name for someone who lived in a valley (Middle English <i>dene</i>, Old English <i>denu</i>) and in part an occupational name for someone who served as a dean, i.e. ecclesiastical supervisor (Latin <i>decanus</i>). The given name also sometimes represents Italian <i>Dino</i> (a short form of names such as <i>Bernardino</i>), as in the case of the American actor and singer  Dean Martin  (  1917–95 )."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicolas \" Dean\" ap was born about 1200, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, \"Y Dean Coch\", was 32 and his mother, Mrs. Y Dean Coch, was 28. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Nicolas Dean ap."}